Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces (if carrots
are on the larger side, halve lengthwise first).

Toss carrots on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil, @Korean chili flakes{1%teaspoon}
(use less if you prefer less heat), and @salt{}. Roast on top rack for ~{10%minutes}
(you'll add more to the sheet then).

Trim @green beans{6%ounce} if necessary. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(separated whites
from greens).

Pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon} in a large #stainless steel pan{} over
medium-high heat. Add beef and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}
per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest and tent with foil to
keep warm. Wipe out pan.

> Swap in chicken or pork for beef; cook chicken until browned and cooked through,
> 3-5 minutes per side.

Once carrots have roasted for 10 minutes, carefully toss green beans on opposite side
of sheet with a drizzle of oil, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Return to top rack until veggies are browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes} more.

When veggies have 5 minutes of roasting remaining, heat a drizzle of oil in pan used
for beef over medium heat. Add scallion whites; cook, stirring, until fragrant,
~{1%minute}.

Add @apricot jam{1%unit}, @ponzu sauce{12%milliliters}, @Sriracha{1%teaspoon}, and
¼ cup water (1⁄3 cup for 4 servings) to pan. Cook, stirring, until thickened,
~{1-3%minutes}.

> If sauce seems too thick, stir in more water 1 tsp at a time.

Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt
and pepper to taste.

> Use pan used for chicken or beef here.

Slice beef crosswise.

> Slice chicken or pork against the grain.

Divide beef and veggies between plates. Spoon sauce over beef and garnish with
scallion greens. Serve.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.